386","–Male":"Zesnulý","–Female":"Zesnulá","1275–Male":"1275–Zesnulý","Between 1310-1332":"od 1310 do 1332","1300":"1300","29 Nov 1329":"29. listopadu 1329","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1329":"1329","Montrose, Angus, Scotland":"Montrose, Angus, Skotsko, United Kingdom","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland","Cromarty, Ross & Cromarty, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland"},"da":{"1300–1333":"1300–1333","1276–1333":"1276–1333","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1329–1386":"1329–1386","1310–1386":"1310–1386","–Male":"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1275–Male":"1275–Afdød","Between 1310-1332":"fra 1310 til 1332","1300":"1300","29 Nov 1329":"29. november 1329","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1329":"1329","Montrose, Angus, Scotland":"Montrose, Angus, Skotland, United Kingdom","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Skotland","Cromarty, Ross & Cromarty, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1300–1333":"1300–1333","1276–1333":"1276–1333","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1329–1386":"1329–1386","1310–1386":"1310–1386","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1275–Male":"1275–Overleden","Between 1310-1332":"van 1310 to 1332","1300":"1300","29 Nov 1329":"29 november 1329","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1329":"1329","Montrose, Angus, Scotland":"Montrose, Angus, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Schotland","Cromarty, Ross & Cromarty, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1300–1333":"1300–1333","1276–1333":"1276–1333","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1329–1386":"1329–1386","1310–1386":"1310–1386","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1275–Male":"1275–Deceased","Between 1310-1332":"from 1310 to 1332","1300":"1300","29 Nov 1329":"29 November 1329","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1329":"1329","Montrose, Angus, Scotland":"Montrose, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland","Cromarty, Ross & Cromarty, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Graham</i> (as well as <i>Grantham</i>, <i>Grandham</i>, and <i>Granham</i>). See also   Grantham  .","Irish (especially Ulster): in Ireland <i>Graham</i> is generally the Scottish name, but it has additionally been adopted as an Anglicized form of both <b>Ó Creacháin</b> (see   Crehan  ) and <b>Ó Gormghaile</b> (see   Gormley  ).","History: The surname Graham was taken to Scotland at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Graham was born in 1300, in Montrose, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sir John Graham Of Abercorn. She married Hugo Dunkeld Earl van Ross on 29 November 1329, in Montrose, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1333, in Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1300–1333":"1300–1333","1276–1333":"1276–1333","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1329–1386":"1329–1386","1310–1386":"1310–1386","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","Between 1310-1332":"1310 kuni 1332","1300":"1300","29 Nov 1329":"29. november 1329","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1329":"1329","Montrose, Angus, Scotland":"Montrose, Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland","Cromarty, Ross & Cromarty, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1300–1333":"1300–1333","1276–1333":"1276–1333","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1329–1386":"1329–1386","1310–1386":"1310–1386","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","Between 1310-1332":"vuodesta 1310 vuoteen 1332","1300":"1300","29 Nov 1329":"29. marraskuuta 1329","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1329":"1329","Montrose, Angus, Scotland":"Montrose, Angus, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland","Cromarty, Ross & Cromarty, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1300–1333":"1300–1333","1276–1333":"1276–1333","1275–1333":"1275–1333","1329–1386":"1329–1386","1310–1386